frameDefinitions: A Fuel, some flammable object or substance, ends up on fire.
A Period or Eventuality is related to its Duration.
An Event continues at a certain Place through Time.
A quantity, the Numerator, can be understood in terms of how it relates to another quantity, the Denominator; the comparison of these two numbers is called the Rate.
An event or state (here termed an Eventuality) or time-Period is described in terms of the Degree to which its duration diverges from a standard.
An Activity takes some Time_length to complete.
frameExamples: Pyongyang agreed to suspend its withdrawal while talks <t>continued</t> with Washington.
I'm not paying the high interest <t>rates</t>.
After a <t>lengthy</t> discussion with the Foreign Minister, Mr. Qian Qichen, they met the Prime Minister.
listRoleDefinitions: The total material currently involved in combustion, including both the parts of the <fen>Fuel</fen> currently undergoing chemical alteration and the partially ionized gas that results from this process.
The entity that is begins to undergo rapid chemical alteration leading to damage or destruction.
This role identifies the <fen>Time</fen> when the <fen>Fire</fen> begins to burn.
This role identifies the <fen>Place</fen> where the <fen>Fire</fen> begins to burn.

A situation, action or event whose duration is being described.  The <fen>Eventuality</fen> occurs as the External Argument if the adjective is used predicatively, or as the modified noun if the adjective is used attributively:
Sometimes a period of time, rather than an event or state is described.
The amount of time that the <fen>Eventuality</fen>, <fen>Period</fen>, or <fen>Entity</fen> lasts.

An item which is metonymically related to an <fen>Eventuality</fen>.  Some common eventualities that are metonymically entailed are the effect of the entity in its capacity as an instrument and the existence of the entity.
Name of the <fen>Event</fen> which is continuing.
When the <fen>Event</fen> occurs.
Where the <fen>Event</fen> takes place.
The number which represents the relative quantities of the <fen>Numerator</fen> and the <fen>Denominator</fen>.
Identifies the quantity whose magnitude is determined relative to the <fen>Denominator</fen>.
The set of things to which the <fen>Rate</fen> pertains.
The quantity whose magnitude is determined relative to the <fen>Numerator</fen>.

A situation, action or event whose duration is being described.  The Eventuality occurs as the External Argument if the adjective is used predicatively, or as the modified noun if the adjective is used attributively: <fex name='Eventuality'>The lecture</fex> was <t>short</t>. We had a <t>lengthy</t> <fex name='Eventuality'>conversation</fex>.

Sometimes these adjectives describe simply a period of time, rather than an event or state.  The Period almost invariably occurs as the modified noun with an attributive adjective: We waited for only a <t>short</t> <fex name='Period'>time</fex>. Use of the drug over a <t>lengthy</t> <fex name='Period'>period</fex> can cause memory loss.
The event which requires some <fen>Time_length</fen> for completion.
The amount of time required for the <fen>Activity</fen>.
A modifier expressing  the deviation of the <fen>Time_length</fen> from the norm.
The individual who performs the <fen>Activity</fen>.
The <fen>Time</fen> at which the <fen>Activity</fen> takes place.
listRoleExamples: <fex>This difficult period</fex> lasted only a short while .
If the film lasts <fex>more than one hour</fex> , I ca n't stay .
